# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-cleveland-blues-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1899-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1899 throughout the world.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1899-in-baseball] Buck Freeman of the Washington Senators leads all batters with 25 home runs during the regular season, more than double hit by Bobby Wallace of the St.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1899-in-baseball] Louis Perfectos, who finished with 12 homers.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1899-in-baseball] Freeman's tally was not surpassed until 1919, when Babe Ruth belted 29 home runs for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1899-in-baseball] The National League would remain at eight teams until 1962.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1901 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 5th in the American League with a record of 68–65.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and played at Oriole Park.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The **1901 Boston Americans season** was the first season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox, and the first season of play for the American League (AL).
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] It resulted in the Americans finishing second in the AL with a record of 79 wins and 57 losses, four games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] On February 11, Jimmy Collins, third baseman for the National League Boston Beaneaters became the first player under contract for the Boston Americans after being offered a contract of $4000 with the added ability to sign subsequent players to contracts.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Collins was joined on March 4 by the outfielder Chick Stahl, who was also from the Beaneaters.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Defecting with Stahl and Collins was the outfielder Buck Freeman.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Yet perhaps the most important signing was that of the 34 year old St.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis Cardinals pitcher Cy Young, who accepted a contract worth $3500 from the Boston Americans.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Vital to the signing of Cy Young from the Cardinals was the signing of Cy Young's catcher in St.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis, Lou Criger; the value that Young gave to Criger and that Criger gave to Young was so strong, that it is unlikely that Young would have signed for the Americans if Criger had not done so.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The total attendance for the Red Sox was 289,448, the second most in the American League (behind the White Sox' 354,350) and more than the crosstown Boston Beaneaters' 146,502.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 12 home runs and had 114 RBIs while recording a .339 batting average.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 38 complete games with a 33–10 record and 1.62 ERA, while striking out 158 in 371+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team had two games end in a tie; August 31 at Detroit Tigers and September 12 at Washington Senators.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Tied games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tied games are counted.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Cy Young led the league in ERA (1.62), shutouts (5; tied with Clark Griffith), strikeouts (158), and wins (33).
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1901 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 31st season of the franchise.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters finished fifth in the National League with a record of 69–69.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1901 Brooklyn Superbas** lost several players to the newly official major league, the American League.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas finished third in the National League with a record of 79–57.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The **1901 Chicago Orphans season** was the 30th season of the Chicago Orphans franchise, the 26th in the National League and the ninth at West Side Park.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The Orphans finished sixth in the National League with a record of 53–86.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-chicago-orphans-season] The team was also known as the Remnants, due to many Orphans players leaving at the end of the 1900 season to join the upstart American League.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The **1901 Cleveland Blues season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] It was the franchise's first in the majors, being one of the original franchises of the American League.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Called the "Blues" or "Bluebirds", the team finished seventh out of eight teams.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Spiders were dissolved after winning only 20 games and losing 134 in the 1899 season along with the Louisville Colonels, Baltimore Orioles, and the Washington Senators, leaving the National League with eight teams to begin the 1900 season.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As a result, 1900 marked the first year since 1886 during which the city of Cleveland did not have a team affiliated with Major League Baseball.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] During this time, Cleveland had a minor league baseball team, known as the Bluebirds or Blues due to their all-blue uniforms, which finished their season with a 63–73 record and finished sixth.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The American League became a major league before the 1901 season.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the American League made the jump to major league status, many players jumped ship, including Cy Young and Nap Lajoie, which led the National League to call them an "outlaw league" in November 1900.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] As the 1901 season came underway in April, and as the war between the two leagues erupted, the Cleveland franchise, now known as the Blues, began its first official season as a Major League Baseball team.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Cleveland Blues played their first game of the season against the Chicago White Stockings on April 24, 1901.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] This was the first games in the history of the American League; three other games scheduled that day were rained out.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The starting lineup consisted of: Ollie Pickering (RF), Jack McCarthy (LF), Frank Genins (CF), Candy LaChance (1B), Bill Bradley (3B), Erve Beck (2B), Bill Hallman (SS), Bob Wood (C), and Bill Hoffer (P).
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] Hoffer allowed seven runs in the first two innings and the Blues failed to recover, as they lost the game 8–2, earning the first loss in American League history.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] In the second game of the season, Beck hit the first home run in American League history off pitcher John Skopec, but the Blues lost again, 7–3.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 9, 1901, Earl Moore threw the first no-hitter in the history of the franchise and the American League.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] The Blues lost to Chicago by a score of 4–2 despite allowing no hits.
[src:1901-cleveland-blues-season/1901-cleveland-blues-season] On May 23, Cleveland scored nine runs with the bases empty and two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning to beat Washington 14–13.
